This type of reasoning shows how convenient it can be to use surface stress arguments. Unfortunately, the surface tension is not particularly well suited to serve as a guiding example, because it has so many special properties: it is tangential, isotropic, and independent of the surface geometry. General surface stresses, including those of membranes, are more complicated, hence the question “with what force per unit length do I have to pull along an open edge to prevent it from snapping back?” will involve a more complex answer. Moreover, this answer will not just involve forces: for surfaces more complicated than tension-dominated ﬁlms surface torques are also important.

